Today’s class focused on software design practices used in Java applications, particularly the DAO (Data Access Object) 
pattern and layered architecture. These design approaches help organize code in a structured way, making applications 
easier to maintain and extend. The mentor explained that in large applications, mixing database code with business 
logic can make programs complex and difficult to manage. The DAO pattern solves this by separating database operations 
from the main application logic.

In the DAO pattern, a separate class is created to handle all database interactions such as inserting, updating, deleting, 
and retrieving data. The main application does not directly communicate with the database. Instead, it calls methods from 
the DAO class. This improves code readability and allows database-related changes to be handled in one place without 
affecting other parts of the program.

The session also covered layered architecture. In this structure, the application is divided into different layers, 
each responsible for a specific task. The presentation layer handles user interaction, the service or business layer 
processes the application logic, and the data access layer communicates with the database. This separation helps developers 
work on different parts of the system independently and improves scalability.

The working flow begins with the presentation layer receiving input from the user. The request is passed to the service 
layer where the main business logic is processed. The service layer then calls the DAO layer to perform database operations. 
The DAO layer executes SQL queries and returns the results back through the layers to the user interface.

Understanding DAO and layered architecture is important because they are commonly used in enterprise Java applications 
to build clean and maintainable systems.